post_text:
The McKinney-Vento Act defines homeless children as ‚Äúindividuals who lack a fixed, regular, and adequate nighttime residence.‚Äù The act provides examples of children who would fall under this definition:

Children and youth sharing housing due to loss of housing, economic hardship or a similar reason
Children and youth living in motels, hotels, trailer parks, or camp grounds due to lack of alternative accommodations
Children and youth living in emergency or transitional shelters
Children and youth abandoned in hospitals
Children and youth whose primary nighttime residence is not ordinarily used as a regular sleeping accommodation (e.g. park benches, etc)
Children and youth living in cars, parks, public spaces, abandoned buildings, substandard housing, bus or train stations
Migratory children and youth living in any of the above situations

post_text:
Hello Calibre Families,

This is Mrs. Kaplan with Calibre happenings. Week 2 went pretty smoothly. We are very pleased with what we are seeing.

Wednesday is an early release day. Classes will end at 12:10 PM. Dismissal for the learning labs are as follows:Lab 1 and 6 will be released at 12:10 PM; labs 2 and 7 will be released at 12:15 PM; labs 3 and 8 will be released at 12:20 PM; labs 4 and 9 are released at 12:25 PM; and labs 5 and 10 will be released at 12:30 PM.

Wednesday is also our 1st spirit day. Students (both at home on campus) and staff may wear a shirt from the college of their choice. Check out Facebook to see which colleges Calibre represents.

Learning lab parents - if your student is not going to be in the lab one day please call the attendance line to let the office know even if they will be logging on from home.

A week from this Monday, on September 7th, we will have no school in observance of Labor Day.

We hope you have a great weekend. Stay safe and healthy and we will see you one way or another on Monday. GO MUSTANGS!!!!

Hello Calibre Families,

The safety protocols will be emailed to you later this morning. Please check your email for the safety guidelines we will be following for in-person learning. As with the COVID-19 health crisis, this is fluid as things have been changing every week. We are following the mandates by Govenor Ducey and Superintendent Kathy Hoffman. We will keep you posted of any changes.

As of now both in-person and online learning will begin on August 17th. We would like to extend the deadline for you to let us know if you would like your student to attend in-person or online learning to Friday, July 24th. Please call the office as we need to start making class lists.

Thank you!

post_text:
YEARBOOK INFO

I hope this finds you and your family doing well.

We wanted to reach out to provide an update with the status of our 2019-2020 yearbook. Due to COVID-19 this year's yearbook is unique from previous years and it is our top priority to ensure yearbooks are delivered to all families that placed an order.

Lifetouch, our yearbook partner, is in uncharted waters with the COVID-19 virus. They have had government-mandated shut-downs in some of their production facilities and social distancing protocols in others that have reduced capacity for printing yearbooks. Be assured that everyone who ordered a yearbook will receive one. However, the delivery of your yearbook may be delayed, resulting in arrival after school is out for the summer.

We will be in touch when we know more about the timing of the delivery of our school's yearbooks.



Please continue to stay healthy and safe.

Good morning parents.

Gov. Doug Ducey has extended the closure of all Arizona schools through the end of this school year. In a joint statement Monday with Superintendent of Public Instruction Kathy Hoffman, Ducey wrote that the decision was made to align with guidance from the federal government.

Our schools executives are meeting this Tuesdayto discuss revised requirements for all of our students. You can expect communication from our meeting on Wednesday afternoon the latest.

We appreciate all your patience during this unfortunate time.

post_text:
Hello Calibre Families,
There seems to be some confusion with morning drop off. We ask that if you are driving up to drop off your student you drive all the way up to the South back parking lot gate. There is no drop off along the fire lane curb near the office.

Also, if your student is late you may NOT just send your student into the office. You must park and come in to sign them in. If a late student is just dropped off you will be called to come back and sign them in.

At dismissal, students may NOT be picked up in front of the office. They need to be picked up in the back parking lot or you can park and come in. We will not send students outside the office.

Thank you for the cooperation.
